In C++, you can generate a signaling NaN by setting the appropriate bits of a floating-point value. The specific implementation may vary depending on the platform and compiler being used, but one common method is to use the `std::numeric_limits` template class from the `<limits>` header to retrieve the bit pattern of a NaN:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <limits>

int main() {
    double nan = std::numeric_limits<double>::quiet_NaN();
    unsigned long long bits = *reinterpret_cast<unsigned long long*>(&nan);
    bits |= 0x0008000000000000;
    double s_nan = *reinterpret_cast<double*>(&bits);
    std::cout << s_nan << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we start by creating a `double` value that represents a quiet NaN by using the `std::numeric_limits<double>::quiet_NaN()` function. We then extract the bit pattern of this value by using a `reinterpret_cast` to convert the address of the `double` value to a pointer to an unsigned long long integer. We can then modify the bit pattern to create a signaling NaN by setting the sixth bit of the mantissa (bit 51) to 1. Finally, we convert the modified bit pattern back to a `double` value using another `reinterpret_cast`.

Note that the use of `reinterpret_cast` is generally considered to be unsafe and implementation-defined, and should be avoided in most cases. It is used here for illustrative purposes only. Additionally, the exact bit pattern used to represent a signaling NaN may be different depending on the platform and compiler being used.
